                            'Ripple Effect' - "Choose Your Food Wisely"

Climate change theory has been debunked by many, but we have data that proves its existence and the momentous 
effects of the change. Although national governments have been working tediously to combat the effects of 
climate change and spread awareness about the same, more light must be shed on the true causes of climate change. 
Data shows that humans at the individual level can make a huge impact on climate change by choosing their 
food wisely.
In [22]:
As we can notice in this interactive visualization, Russia has one of the highest rises in temperature (like 
Canada). The lowest rise in temperature is in Southern Africa, the hottest continent in the world(as distinctly
visible on the globe highlighted in blue).  

In the Visualization, dark blue indicates the least rise in temperature, and crimson indicates the highest rise. 
This visualization clearly shows that colder regions are more rapidly becoming warmer than others which has 
resulted in the reduction of snow cover and the rising sea level.

The graphics below demonstrate a trend whereby CO2 emissions and the average worldwide land temperature have

In [24]:
Looking at the below graphs, we can see that various food items in this dataset, such as beef, lamb, mutton, 
cheese, dark chocolate, and coffee, have total emissions of more than 15 kg CO2 per 1000 Calories of created 
product. They can therefore be regarded as having the largest carbon footprints of all products. Most of these 
food items are derived from animals. The Land Use trend of these products also resembles the total emission
trend; Thus we can conclude that the more we consume the animal-based product, the more impact it will have 
in terms of carbon footprint.
In [25]:
As concluded earlier, meat consumption is associated with a higher carbon footprint. 

Population increase accompanied by an increase in per capita consumption has led to a high increase in overall 
global meat consumption over the years as seen in the graphs below. 

When looking on a global scale we see the largest rise in poultry, which nearly tripled, this could be due to 
the higher efficiency (the amount of food needed to increase the weight of the animal by one) of the animal. We 
also see a steep increase in the consumption of pigs around 1990 and an increase in the consumption of Beef 
around the world in the year 2000. 

This overall increase in meat consumption over the last 30 years can be correlated with a continuous increase in 
CO2 emission.
In [26]:
There is another graphic that indicates that there is a constant decrease in forest cover globally showing its 
negative correlation with animal-based food production. As the production of meat and the human population has 
increased over the years, forest cover has been reducing continuously. Previously, we learned that the production
of meat consumes the maximum amount of land (for animal farming) which in turn leads to deforestation resulting 
in a sharp forest cover depletion. This further worsens the CO2 levels as there are fewer trees to absorb 
atmospheric CO2.
In [27]:
Research indicates that climate change is attributed to an increase in natural disasters causing significant loss 
of life and governments losing billions of dollars.

The first of below graphs shows the number of global natural disasters each year from 1950 to 2018. The 
number of natural disasters per year has exploded since the 1960s, particularly due to increases in flooding and 
extreme weather (hurricanes and cyclones). The economic losses brought on by natural disasters each year are 
depicted in the bottom graph. Even though the graph does not show a continuous increase but demonstrates a strong 
upward tendency.
In [28]:
Natural disasters not only cause monetary losses, but also affect millions of people globally directly or 
indirectly.

The bar graph shows the global total number of people affected by natural disasters. This is defined as the sum 
of the injured, affected, and those left homeless after a disaster. Due to the ripple effect of climate change, 
meat consumption can be correlated with natural disasters and ultimately millions of people being affected 
massively in the last 40-50 years.

In [30]:
As predicted in the graph below, we are on schedule to meet the threshold of an increase in temperature by 1.5 
degree celsius, demonstrating how even slight variations in CO2 emissions today can mount up over time. We 
generated the prediction using a completely fictitious scenario in which CO2 emissions reach a certain number and 
then remain constant at 420 ppm. As you can see, CO2 significantly affects the temperature, as the upper bound 
crosses the 2-degree threshold which would be disastrous. This proves that making considerable efforts to lower 
CO2 emissions will pay off in the long run. The point stands - It is still possible to take action to achieve 
the lower bound.

since the 18th century. The biggest temperature changes were in Europe and South America. We see that colder 
countries (situated to the North) had the biggest increase in Temperature than the overall South. So we can 
conclude that colder countries are getting warmer more rapidly than hotter countries.
